# Lab 02 — MVCC & Dead Tuples

> Understanding how PostgreSQL handles updates without overwriting existing rows.

---

## Objective

One of PostgreSQL's biggest strengths is its ability to handle many users reading and writing data at the same time.

Instead of overwriting existing rows during an UPDATE or DELETE operation, PostgreSQL creates a new version of the row.

This behavior is called **Multi-Version Concurrency Control (MVCC)**.

Understanding MVCC explains why PostgreSQL needs VACUUM, why dead tuples exist, and why PostgreSQL performs well under concurrent workloads.

---

# Key Concepts

## MVCC

MVCC stands for **Multi-Version Concurrency Control**.

Rather than modifying an existing row, PostgreSQL creates a new version whenever a row is updated.

This allows multiple transactions to access the database safely without constantly blocking each other.

---

## Tuple

A tuple is PostgreSQL's physical representation of a row.

For example:

| id | name |
|----|------|
|1|Philip|

Internally this row is stored as a tuple inside a page.

Whenever the row is updated, PostgreSQL creates another tuple instead of replacing the original one.

---

## UPDATE

Consider the following query:

```sql
UPDATE users
SET name = 'Phil'
WHERE id = 1;
```

Many people assume PostgreSQL changes the existing row.

Instead, PostgreSQL:

1. Creates a new tuple containing the updated data.
2. Marks the previous tuple as obsolete.
3. Makes the new tuple visible to future transactions.

The original tuple remains on disk until PostgreSQL can safely remove it.

---

## Dead Tuple

A dead tuple is an old row version that is no longer needed by any active transaction.

Dead tuples still occupy space inside database pages until they are cleaned up.

PostgreSQL removes these dead tuples using **VACUUM**, which we will cover in the next lab.

---

# How MVCC Works

Imagine the following row exists.

| id | name |
|----|------|
|1|Philip|

An UPDATE is executed.

```sql
UPDATE users
SET name = 'Phil'
WHERE id = 1;
```

Internally PostgreSQL creates a new tuple.

```
Original Tuple (Old Version)

id = 1
name = Philip

        │
        │ UPDATE
        ▼

New Tuple (Current Version)

id = 1
name = Phil
```

The application only sees the newest visible tuple.

The old tuple becomes a dead tuple once it is no longer required.

---

# Why PostgreSQL Uses MVCC

Imagine two users access the same row.

- Alice is reading customer information.
- Bob updates that customer at the same time.

Without MVCC, one user would often have to wait for the other.

With MVCC:

- Alice continues reading the old version.
- Bob creates a new version.
- Both operations continue safely.

This greatly improves concurrency and reduces locking.

---

# Why This Matters for Support Engineers

Imagine a customer says:

> "Our database keeps getting larger even though we rarely insert new rows."

A Support Engineer should consider:

- Are rows being updated frequently?
- Are dead tuples accumulating?
- Is VACUUM running correctly?
- Is table bloat increasing?

Understanding MVCC is the first step toward answering these questions.

