# Questions

## 1. What is MVCC?

MVCC (Multi-Version Concurrency Control) is PostgreSQL's method of managing concurrent transactions by creating new versions of rows instead of overwriting existing ones.

---

## 2. Why doesn't PostgreSQL overwrite rows during an UPDATE?

Overwriting a row could interfere with other transactions that are still reading the old data.

Creating a new tuple allows readers and writers to work simultaneously without blocking each other.

---

## 3. What is a dead tuple?

A dead tuple is an old version of a row that is no longer visible to active transactions.

It remains on disk until VACUUM removes it.

---

## 4. Why doesn't PostgreSQL remove dead tuples immediately?

Another transaction may still need to read the old version of the row.

PostgreSQL waits until it is safe before reclaiming the space.

---

## 5. How does MVCC improve database performance?

MVCC allows multiple users to read and update data concurrently with minimal locking.

This improves performance and scalability for busy databases.

